package lenses

import "github.com/sw6n297mn8-maker/mesh-spec/architecture/artifact-schemas:artifact_schemas"

designTokensAndSystematicComposition: artifact_schemas.#AnalyticalLens & {
id:     "lens-design-tokens-and-systematic-composition"
name:   "Design Tokens e Composição Sistemática"

purpose: "Orientar decisões sobre como usar design tokens como sistema de composição — consistência visual, themability e manutenção escalável."
status: "draft"

trigger: {
	conditions: [
		"a decisão envolve como definir design tokens (spacing, colors, typography, sizing, shadows, radii) como foundation do design system",
		"a decisão envolve como garantir consistência visual entre componentes, telas, personas e dispositivos",
		"a decisão envolve como estruturar component library para B2B multisided platform com density modes e themes",
		"a decisão envolve como compor componentes complexos (dashboard, table, form) a partir de primitivos simples (button, input, badge)",
		"a decisão envolve como design tokens habilitam density modes (compact, default, spacious), themes (light, dark) e white-labeling",
		"a decisão envolve como manter design system com solo founder onde agentes IA geram a maior parte do UI code",
		"a decisão envolve como design system governa output visual de agentes para prevenir inconsistência",
		"a decisão envolve trade-offs entre design system completo (100 componentes) e minimal viable (10 componentes) para MVP",
	]
	keywords: [
		"design tokens", "tokens", "variáveis de design", "CSS variables", "custom properties",
		"design system", "sistema de design", "component library", "UI library",
		"spacing", "sizing", "border-radius", "elevation", "shadow", "z-index",
		"breakpoint", "responsive", "grid", "layout", "column",
		"component", "componente", "primitive", "compound", "pattern", "template",
		"atomic design", "atoms", "molecules", "organisms",
		"consistency", "consistência", "reutilização", "reuse", "DRY",
		"density mode", "compact", "default", "spacious",
		"theme", "dark mode", "light mode", "white-label",
		"Tailwind", "Figma variables", "style dictionary", "token pipeline",
		"minimal viable design system", "MVDS",
	]
	excludeWhen: [
		"a decisão é sobre valores específicos de tipografia (escala, weights) — usar typographic-systems-for-dense-interfaces",
		"a decisão é sobre valores específicos de cor (semantic, palette) — usar color-as-functional-language",
		"a decisão é sobre density strategy e composição de dashboard — usar information-density-design",
		"a decisão é sobre patterns de interação (forms, feedback, batch) — usar interaction-patterns-for-professional-tools",
		"a decisão é sobre tipos de charts e encoding visual — usar data-visualization-semiotics",
	]
	rationale: "Design tokens são a foundation layer que habilita todos os outros aspectos do design visual. TS define typographic scale; CL define cores; ID define density strategy; IP define interaction patterns. DT codifica TODAS essas decisões em tokens consumíveis por componentes, tornando possível: mudar density mode (compact → spacious) via token override sem tocar em componente. Mudar theme (light → dark) via token override. Mudar brand (white-label para FIDC) via token override. Sem tokens: cada componente hardcoda seus próprios valores, inconsistência prolifera organicamente, e qualquer mudança global requer search-and-replace em todo o codebase. Na Mesh AI-native com agentes gerando UI code: tokens são constraints que agente consome para produzir output visualmente consistente — sem tokens, N sessões de agente produzem N estilos visuais diferentes. Com tokens: N sessões produzem 1 estilo consistente governado por design system."
}

concepts: [
	{
		id:         "dt-token-architecture"
		name:       "Arquitetura de Tokens: 3 Camadas de Abstração (Global → Alias → Component)"
		nature:     "theoretical"
		role:       "framework"
		definition: "Design token architecture formalizada por Salesforce Lightning Design System (2019, evoluída 2024+): tokens organizados em 3 camadas de abstração crescente: **Layer 1 — Global tokens (raw values):** valores primitivos sem significado semântico. São o vocabulário base. color-blue-500: #3b82f6. color-green-700: #15803d. spacing-4: 16px. font-size-14: 14px. shadow-md: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0,0,0,0.1). Nomeados por: type + scale position. Não referenciam contexto de uso. **Layer 2 — Alias tokens (semantic mapping):** mapeiam globals para significados semânticos. color-success-primary: {value: color-green-700}. color-text-primary: {value: color-gray-900}. spacing-gap-md: {value: spacing-4}. font-size-body: {value: font-size-14}. surface-card: {value: color-white}. Nomeados por: role/purpose + variant. Carregam significado: 'success-primary' comunica intent. **Layer 3 — Component tokens (component-specific):** mapeiam alias para contextos de componente específico. button-padding-horizontal: {value: spacing-gap-md}. badge-text-color: {value: color-success-primary}. table-row-height: {value: spacing-9}. kpi-card-padding: {value: spacing-gap-md}. Nomeados por: component + property. Optionais — muitos componentes podem referenciar alias diretamente. Úteis quando componente precisa de valor que difere do alias padrão. Conceito de 'token-driven development' (2024+): developers e agentes trabalham com tokens, nunca com raw values. Se designer diz 'make this green': developer usa --color-success-primary, não #15803d. Se designer diz 'more space here': developer usa next token in spacing scale, não arbitrary 18px. Token muda: todos os componentes que referenciam atualizam simultaneamente. Concepto de 'token as contract' (2024+): tokens são o contrato entre design e implementation. Designer define: 'success é verde, body é 14px, gap é 16px.' Developer implementa: variáveis CSS que referenciam esses valores. Mudança no contrato (designer muda verde para teal): propagação automática. Sem token: mudança requer grep + manual replacement."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, 3 layers: **Global:** color scale: gray-50..gray-900 (10 steps), blue-50..blue-900, green-50..green-900, red-50..red-900, yellow-50..yellow-900, orange-50..orange-900. ~60 color globals. Spacing scale: 1(4px), 2(8px), 3(12px), 4(16px), 5(20px), 6(24px), 8(32px), 10(40px), 12(48px). 9 spacing globals. Font-size scale: 11, 12, 13, 14, 16, 18, 20, 24, 28px. 9 font globals. Font-weight: 400, 500, 600, 700. 4 weight globals. Border-radius: sm(4px), md(6px), lg(8px), xl(12px), full(9999px). 5 radius globals. Shadow: none, sm, md, lg. 4 shadow globals. Total globals: ~95 values. **Alias:** color-text-primary: gray-900. color-text-secondary: gray-600. color-text-muted: gray-500. color-surface-page: gray-50. color-surface-card: white. color-success-primary: green-700. color-success-subtle: green-50. (etc × 5 intents). spacing-gap-sm: spacing-2. spacing-gap-md: spacing-4. spacing-gap-lg: spacing-6. font-size-xs..font-size-xl (6 steps from TS). line-height-tight, line-height-normal, line-height-headline. Total alias: ~50 values. **Component (selective):** kpi-card-padding: spacing-gap-md. table-row-height-compact: 24px. table-row-height-default: 36px. button-radius: radius-md. badge-radius: radius-full. Total component: ~20 values (only where needed)."
		meshImplication: "Token implementation: (1) CSS custom properties para todos os tokens: :root { --color-gray-900: #111827; --color-text-primary: var(--color-gray-900); --kpi-card-padding: var(--spacing-gap-md); }. Components: p { color: var(--color-text-primary); }. .kpi-card { padding: var(--kpi-card-padding); }. (2) file structure: tokens/globals.css (raw values), tokens/aliases.css (semantic), tokens/components.css (component-specific). Or: single tokens.css with sections. Imported by all components. (3) naming convention: --{layer}-{category}-{property}-{variant}. Globals: --color-blue-500, --spacing-4, --font-size-14. Aliases: --color-text-primary, --spacing-gap-md, --font-size-body. Components: --button-padding, --table-row-height. Predictable: developer or agent can guess token name. (4) no magic numbers: CI lint rule — every color, spacing, font-size, border-radius, shadow in component files must reference token variable. Raw value (color: #3b82f6, padding: 16px, font-size: 14px) → CI warning. Forces token usage. (5) token documentation: design system docs list all tokens with: name, value, usage examples, visual swatch (for colors). Agente reads docs to select correct token. 'Need body text color → --color-text-primary. Need KPI card padding → --kpi-card-padding.' (6) token count discipline: ~165 total tokens (95 global + 50 alias + 20 component). Not 500. Every token earns existence by being referenced ≥3 times. Token referenced once: probably not needed (inline the value or use parent token). Anti-pattern: 500 tokens where 300 are referenced once — token sprawl is as bad as no tokens (developer can't find the right one among 500 options)."
		rationale: "Salesforce Lightning 2019: 3-layer architecture. Token-driven development 2024+. Token as contract 2024+. Na Mesh, ~165 tokens encode entire visual system. Change --spacing-gap-md from 16px to 12px: every gap in every component updates. Zero search-and-replace. Token change = global change."
	},
	{
		id:         "dt-component-composition"
		name:       "Composição de Componentes: Primitivos → Compounds → Patterns → Templates"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "framework"
		reviewCadence: "semi-annual"
		definition: "Frost (2016, Atomic Design): hierarchy de abstração para UI components: atoms (indivisible elements) → molecules (simple groups of atoms) → organisms (complex groups of molecules) → templates (page-level structures) → pages (templates with real data). Conceito adaptado para B2B design system: **Primitives (atoms):** Button, Input, Select, Checkbox, Badge, Icon, Text, Avatar, Spinner, Skeleton. Each: single responsibility, styled by tokens, no business logic. **Compounds (molecules/organisms):** MetricCard = Text[xl,bold] + Text[sm] + Sparkline + DeltaIndicator. FormField = Text[label] + Input + Text[error]. StatusBadge = Badge + Icon + Text (from CL semantic system). DataTable = TableHeader + TableRow[] + TableFooter + Pagination + ActionBar. Toast = Icon + Text + Button[dismiss]. **Patterns (recurring compositions):** KPIRow = 4× MetricCard in responsive grid. OperationForm = FormField[] + FileUpload + Button. FilterBar = Select[] + Input[search] + Button[apply]. **Templates (page layouts):** DashboardTemplate = KPIRow + DataTable + ChartSection. DetailTemplate = Breadcrumb + Header + Content + SidePanel. FormTemplate = ProgressIndicator + OperationForm + Navigation. Conceito de 'composition over configuration' (2023+): em vez de 1 mega-component com 30 props (BarChart com props para: type, stacked, horizontal, grouped, colors, labels, animations, legends, tooltips, themes...), compor components especializados: HorizontalBarChart, StackedBarChart, GroupedBarChart. Cada um: focused, simpler API, fewer props. Compound component é composed from primitives, not configured from god-component."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, component inventory: **Primitives (10 core):** Button (primary, secondary, danger, ghost; sizes: sm, md, lg; states: default, hover, focus, active, disabled, loading). Input (text, number, currency, percentage, date; with label, placeholder, error, disabled). Select (single, multi; searchable, creatable). Checkbox (individual, group; indeterminate for header). Badge (semantic colors from CL; sizes: sm, md). Icon (from Lucide icon set; sizes: 16, 20, 24px). Text (sizes from TS scale; weights; colors from CL text tokens). Sparkline (data, threshold, color). Skeleton (types: card, table-row, text-line, chart). Spinner (sizes: sm, md, lg). **Compounds (8 core):** MetricCard (value + label + Sparkline + DeltaIndicator + click-to-drill). FormField (label + Input + validation message + help text). StatusBadge (Badge + Icon + text; status enum → CL semantic mapping). DataTable (header + rows + sort + filter + checkbox + pagination + ActionBar). Toast (icon + message + action button + dismiss; semantic type). Modal (overlay + header + content + footer buttons; sizes: sm, md, lg). SidePanel (overlay right; header + content + footer; push or overlay layout). CommandPalette (search input + results list + keyboard navigation). **Patterns:** KPIRow (MetricCard[] in responsive grid — 4 on desktop, 2 on tablet, 1 on mobile). FilterBar (Select + Input[search] + DateRange + Button[apply/clear]). ActionBar (count label + Button[] for batch actions; sticky). ScoreGauge (from DV fintech-specific). ConcentrationChart, VintageChart, WaterfallChart (from DV)."
		meshImplication: "Composition guidelines: (1) primitives consume tokens directly — Button uses --button-padding, --color-brand-primary, --font-size-base, --radius-md. Every visual property from token. (2) compounds compose primitives — MetricCard composes Text + Sparkline + DeltaIndicator. MetricCard doesn't define font-size — it uses Text[xl] which uses --font-size-xl. No visual properties at compound level — inherited from primitives which inherit from tokens. (3) props simplicity — compound accepts data props (value, label, trendData) not style props (fontSize, color, padding). Style comes from tokens via primitives. Developer: <MetricCard value='R$2.3M' label='Lastro Total' trendData={[1.8,2.0,2.1,2.3]} />. Not: <MetricCard value='R$2.3M' fontSize={24} fontWeight={700} color='#111827' padding={16} />. (4) component API documentation — each component has: description (what it does), props (name, type, required/optional, default), usage guidelines (when to use, when NOT to use), code example, visual example. Written for agent consumption: structured, concise, with examples (dp-agent-consumability). (5) new pattern evaluation — when UI pattern appears that doesn't match existing component: evaluate: (a) does it appear ≥3 times? → create DS component. (b) does it appear once? → acceptable as one-off with token usage (not hardcoded values). (c) does it partially match existing component? → extend existing with variant, not new component. (6) component count discipline — target: 18-25 components total for MVP (10 primitives + 8 compounds). Not 100. Each component earns existence by being used ≥3 times. Unused component: remove. Under-used: evaluate consolidation. Anti-pattern: 'god component' DataTable with 45 props covering every possible table variation — impossible to document, impossible for agent to use correctly, impossible to maintain. Better: DataTable (core: sort, filter, pagination) + BatchTable (extends DataTable + checkbox + ActionBar) + EditableTable (extends DataTable + inline edit)."
		dependsOn: ["dt-token-architecture"]
		crossDependsOn: [{
			lensId:    "lens-documentation-as-product"
			conceptId: "dp-agent-consumability"
			context:   "DP defines agent-consumable documentation: structured, concise, self-contained with examples. DT component docs follow DP principles: component API is structured (props with types), usage is concise (when/when not), examples are self-contained code snippets. Agent reads component doc → uses component correctly. DP says 'design for context window'; DT says 'component docs that agent parses in 500 tokens: description + props + example = sufficient for correct usage'."
		}]
		rationale: "Frost 2016: Atomic Design. Composition over configuration 2023+. Na Mesh, 18-25 components composed from tokens: consistent UI. Agent uses <MetricCard value='...' /> — component handles styling via tokens. Agent doesn't decide font-size, color, or padding. System decides. Consistency by construction, not by discipline."
	},
	{
		id:         "dt-density-mode-tokens"
		name:       "Tokens de Density Mode: Compact, Default, Spacious via Token Override"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "method"
		reviewCadence: "semi-annual"
		definition: "Density modes (ID lens: id-density-calibration-per-persona) são implementados via token override — mesmos componentes, diferentes valores de token. Conceito de 'mode as token layer' (2024+): density mode é uma layer de tokens que overrides alias tokens. Default mode: alias tokens have their standard values. Compact mode: override layer reduces spacing, font-sizes, heights. Spacious mode: override layer increases them. Component code: unchanged. Implementation: CSS class on root element that redefines token values. body.density-compact { --spacing-gap-md: 8px; --font-size-body: 13px; --table-row-height: 24px; }. Component: .table-row { height: var(--table-row-height); } — renders 24px in compact, 36px in default, 48px in spacious. Zero component code change."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, 3 density modes com token overrides: **Compact (FIDC default):** --font-size-xs: 11px; --font-size-base: 13px; --font-size-xl: 20px. --spacing-gap-sm: 4px; --spacing-gap-md: 8px; --spacing-gap-lg: 12px. --table-row-height: 24px. --kpi-card-padding: 12px. --line-height-tight: 1.2. Result: maximum data density on 1440p+ screens. ~30 table rows visible. **Default (construtora default):** --font-size-xs: 12px; --font-size-base: 14px; --font-size-xl: 24px. --spacing-gap-sm: 8px; --spacing-gap-md: 16px; --spacing-gap-lg: 24px. --table-row-height: 36px. --kpi-card-padding: 16px. --line-height-tight: 1.3. Result: balanced density and readability. ~18 table rows visible. **Spacious (fornecedor default):** --font-size-xs: 13px; --font-size-base: 16px; --font-size-xl: 28px. --spacing-gap-sm: 12px; --spacing-gap-md: 24px; --spacing-gap-lg: 32px. --table-row-height: 48px. --kpi-card-padding: 24px. --line-height-tight: 1.4. Result: comfortable mobile-first experience. ~10 table rows visible on mobile."
		meshImplication: "Density implementation: (1) CSS class approach: body.density-compact { ... overrides ... }. Applied via: user preference (settings), persona default (FIDC auto-compact), or responsive (mobile forces minimum sizes). (2) token matrix — spreadsheet/table documenting: token name × mode = value. --font-size-base: compact=13, default=14, spacious=16. Reviewed and maintained as design system artifact. (3) mobile safety floor: even in compact mode on mobile: --font-size-base ≥ 14px. --touch-target ≥ 44px. Mobile overrides compact for safety: @media (max-width: 640px) { .density-compact { --font-size-base: max(14px, var(--font-size-base)); } }. (4) mode toggle: user-facing toggle in settings or toolbar. Persist per-user. Default per persona but overridable. FIDC power user who wants spacious for presentation: can switch. Construtora novato who wants compact: can switch. (5) testing: 3 modes × critical screens. Each screen must: (a) render without overflow/overlap in all modes. (b) maintain hierarchy (headline > body > caption in all modes). (c) maintain readability (no text below mode minimum). (6) implementation effort: token extraction (one-time migration from hardcoded values): 20-40 hours. Mode definition: 4 hours. Testing: 8 hours. Total: ~35-50 hours. After: any future density adjustment is token change (minutes, not hours). Anti-pattern: 'compact mode' implemented by shrinking every component by 80% via CSS scale transform — text blurry, click targets too small, not real density adjustment. Token override: real values change, rendering is native quality."
		dependsOn: ["dt-token-architecture"]
		crossDependsOn: [{
			lensId:    "lens-information-density-design"
			conceptId: "id-density-calibration-per-persona"
			context:   "ID defines density strategy per persona: FIDC = compact, construtora = default, fornecedor = spacious. DT implements: body.density-compact sets token overrides that make every component compact. ID is the strategy ('what density for whom'); DT is the implementation ('how density is achieved via token override'). ID defines the target; DT provides the mechanism."
		}]
		rationale: "Mode as token layer 2024+. Na Mesh, same DataTable component renders: 24px rows for FIDC (compact, 30 rows visible), 36px for construtora (default, 18 rows), 48px for fornecedor (spacious, 10 rows). Zero code duplication. Token overrides only. Investment: ~40 hours. Payoff: every future density adjustment is minutes of token change."
	},
	{
		id:         "dt-theme-tokens"
		name:       "Tokens de Theme: Light, Dark e White-Label via Token Override"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "method"
		reviewCadence: "annual"
		definition: "Themes work identically to density modes: token override layer. Light theme: alias tokens map to light values. Dark theme: alias tokens map to dark values. White-label (FIDC brand): brand tokens map to client brand colors. Conceito de 'theme as token layer' (2024+): mesma arquitetura de density applied to visual theme. body.theme-dark { --color-surface-page: var(--color-gray-900); --color-text-primary: var(--color-gray-100); --color-success-primary: hsl(142, 71%, 55%); /* lighter green for dark bg */ }. Component: p { color: var(--color-text-primary); } — renders dark text on light bg OR light text on dark bg. Zero component change. Conceito de 'semantic color preservation across themes' (2024+): semantic meaning is preserved across themes. Success is green in light AND dark — different shade, same meaning. Error is red in both. Brand primary is blue in both (or whatever brand color is). Meaning is constant; visual representation adapts to background."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, theme layers: **Light (default):** --color-surface-page: gray-50. --color-surface-card: white. --color-text-primary: gray-900. --color-text-secondary: gray-600. --color-success-primary: hsl(142, 71%, 29%). --color-error-primary: hsl(0, 85%, 45%). --shadow-sm: 0 1px 2px rgba(0,0,0,0.05). **Dark (optional):** --color-surface-page: hsl(220, 20%, 10%). --color-surface-card: hsl(220, 18%, 14%). --color-text-primary: gray-100. --color-text-secondary: gray-400. --color-success-primary: hsl(142, 71%, 55%). /* lighter for dark bg */ --color-error-primary: hsl(0, 85%, 60%). --shadow-sm: 0 1px 2px rgba(0,0,0,0.3). /* stronger shadow for dark bg */ **FIDC white-label (future):** --color-brand-primary: var(--fidc-client-brand-color). --color-brand-primary-hover: darker(--fidc-client-brand-color). Semantic colors: UNCHANGED. Green success, red error, yellow warning — same across all FIDC clients. Only brand color changes."
		meshImplication: "Theme implementation: (1) theme file per theme: themes/light.css, themes/dark.css, themes/fidc-{client}.css. Each overrides alias tokens. (2) theme selection: user preference (settings toggle). System preference detection: @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) { :root { /* dark tokens */ } }. Persist: localStorage or user profile on server. (3) semantic preservation: when creating dark theme, for each semantic color: re-compute to maintain: (a) ≥4.5:1 contrast against dark backgrounds (re-verify all pairs). (b) same hue family (green stays green, red stays red). (c) adjust lightness upward for dark backgrounds (dark green on dark bg → lighter green on dark bg). (4) white-label: only brand tokens change. Semantic: constant. Construtora sees Mesh brand colors. FIDC sees their own brand colors. Both: same green for success, same red for error. (5) combinability: density + theme are independent layers. body.density-compact.theme-dark → compact sizing + dark colors. Both applied via token override. No interaction conflicts (spacing doesn't depend on color). (6) priority: light theme first. Ship complete and tested. Dark theme: subsequent release (doubles color testing effort). White-label: per-client customization when FIDC onboards (brand color only — low effort since only --color-brand-* tokens change). (7) dark mode testing: every text/background pair re-verified. Light text on dark bg has different contrast characteristics than dark text on light bg. Cannot assume: 'if light mode passes, dark mode passes.' Dedicated dark mode contrast audit required. Anti-pattern: dark mode implemented by CSS filter: invert(100%) — inverts everything including images, semantic colors (green becomes magenta), and brand colors. Not a theme — a visual distortion."
		dependsOn: ["dt-token-architecture"]
		crossDependsOn: [{
			lensId:    "lens-color-as-functional-language"
			conceptId: "cl-dark-mode-and-theming"
			context:   "CL defines semantic color adaptation for dark mode: lighter greens, lighter reds to maintain contrast on dark backgrounds. DT theme tokens implement: dark theme file overrides color tokens with CL-specified dark values. CL says 'success-primary in dark mode is hsl(142, 71%, 55%)'; DT encodes as --color-success-primary: hsl(142, 71%, 55%) in themes/dark.css. CL defines values; DT provides implementation infrastructure."
		}]
		rationale: "Theme as token layer 2024+. Semantic preservation 2024+. Na Mesh, light + dark + white-label: all achieved via token override. Same components render differently based on active theme. Investment: theme file creation (~8 hours per theme). FIDC white-label: ~2 hours per client (brand color only). Scale: unlimited themes, zero component changes."
	},
	{
		id:         "dt-responsive-layout-tokens"
		name:       "Tokens de Layout Responsivo: Breakpoints, Grid e Adaptive Composition"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "property"
		reviewCadence: "semi-annual"
		definition: "Layout tokens define: breakpoints (when layout changes), grid (how content is organized), and adaptive behaviors (what changes at each breakpoint). Conceito de 'breakpoint-responsive tokens' (2024+): tokens whose values change per breakpoint. Not just layout (columns) but content-level (font-size, spacing, visibility). @media (max-width: 640px) { :root { --font-size-base: 16px; --grid-columns: 1; --kpi-per-row: 1; } }. @media (min-width: 1024px) { :root { --font-size-base: 14px; --grid-columns: 12; --kpi-per-row: 4; } }. Conceito de 'content priority at breakpoints' (2024+, from ID lens responsive-density): at each breakpoint, not just layout changes — content changes. Mobile: show P0 (essential). Tablet: show P0 + P1. Desktop: show P0 + P1 + P2. Implementation: components accept priority prop; CSS shows/hides based on breakpoint."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, responsive tokens: **Breakpoints:** --bp-mobile: 640px. --bp-tablet: 1024px. --bp-desktop: 1440px. --bp-wide: 1920px. **Grid:** mobile: 1 column (stacked). Tablet: 8 columns. Desktop: 12 columns. Wide: 12 columns with max-width container. **Adaptive per breakpoint:** mobile (<640px): KPIRow = 1 card stacked. Table = essential columns only (3-4). Sidebar = hidden (bottom nav). Charts = hidden or simplified. tablet (640-1024px): KPIRow = 2 cards per row. Table = medium columns (6-8). Sidebar = collapsible. Charts = simplified. desktop (1024-1440px): KPIRow = 4 cards per row. Table = full columns. Sidebar = persistent. Charts = full. wide (>1440px): same as desktop with more whitespace or additional context panels."
		meshImplication: "Layout implementation: (1) CSS Grid with token-based columns: .layout { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(var(--grid-columns), 1fr); gap: var(--spacing-gap-md); }. Breakpoint changes --grid-columns: mobile = 1, tablet = 8, desktop = 12. (2) component visibility by priority: <TableColumn priority={1}> shown always. <TableColumn priority={2}> shown on tablet+. <TableColumn priority={3}> shown on desktop+. CSS: @media (max-width: 640px) { [data-priority='2'], [data-priority='3'] { display: none; } }. (3) sidebar behavior: desktop: persistent sidebar (200-240px width). Tablet: collapsible (hamburger toggle). Mobile: hidden (bottom navigation instead). Transition: CSS media query changes sidebar display and main content width. (4) KPIRow adaptive: grid-template-columns changes by breakpoint. Desktop: repeat(4, 1fr). Tablet: repeat(2, 1fr). Mobile: 1fr. Same MetricCard component, different grid placement. (5) max-width container: wide screens (>1440px): content has max-width to prevent extreme line lengths. --container-max-width: 1440px. Centered with auto margins. Prevents: 3000px wide table on ultrawide monitor (illegible). (6) touch targets: mobile breakpoint: all interactive elements ≥ 44px × 44px. Token: --touch-target-min: 44px. Components: min-height: var(--touch-target-min) on mobile. (7) testing: each persona's primary workflow on primary device. Fornecedor: submit antecipação on mobile (375px). Construtora: review dashboard on desktop (1440px). FIDC: analyze operations on wide desktop (1920px). Workflow must complete without device switch."
		dependsOn: ["dt-token-architecture"]
		rationale: "Breakpoint-responsive tokens 2024+. Content priority at breakpoints 2024+. Na Mesh, same components render: mobile (1 column, essential content, touch targets) → desktop (12 columns, full content, precise pointer). Token-driven breakpoints: layout adapts without component code changes."
