	{
		id:         "dt-design-system-governance-for-ai"
		name:       "Governança de Design System para AI: Tokens como Constraints para Agentes"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "method"
		reviewCadence: "quarterly"
		definition: "Em AI-native development, design system tem dual role: (1) traditional — visual consistency para humanos que usam o produto. (2) AI-specific — constraint system para agentes que geram UI code. Sem constraints: agente usa qualquer valor que 'parece razoável' — cada sessão produz estilo levemente diferente. Com constraints: agente consome tokens e componentes, produzindo output consistente governado pelo sistema. Conceito de 'design system as prompt' (2024+): CLAUDE.md e component docs são, efetivamente, prompt engineering para agentes que geram UI. Quanto mais claro o prompt (docs), melhor o output (UI). Component docs com structured API + usage guidelines + examples = agent generates correct UI. Component docs vagos ou ausentes = agent guesses, inconsistency follows. Conceito de 'CI as design system enforcer' (2024+): CI pipeline valida que agent output complies with design system: (a) lint for raw values — hardcoded hex, px, font-size → warning. (b) lint for missing tokens — new visual property not referencing token → warning. (c) lint for unknown components — custom div with styles where DS component exists → suggestion. (d) accessibility checks — contrast ratios, ARIA labels. CI transforms design system from 'guidelines' to 'enforced rules.'"
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh AI-native, DS governance: (1) **CLAUDE.md instruction:** 'UI components: use design system components from @mesh/ui. Tokens from tokens.css. Never use raw hex values, raw pixel values, or inline font-sizes. For new UI: compose existing components. If no component matches need: document the gap, create as new DS component with tokens — not one-off styled div.' (2) **component docs as agent prompt:** cada componente em design system docs: MetricCard — description: 'displays single KPI with value, label, trend, and comparison.' Props: value (string, required), label (string, required), trendData (number[], optional — 8-12 points), comparison (string, optional), onClick (function, optional — drill-down). When to use: 'KPI display on dashboards.' When NOT to use: 'detailed metrics (use table). Multiple related values (use table or custom layout).' Example: <MetricCard value='R$2.3M' label='Lastro Total' trendData={[1.8,1.9,2.1,2.3]} comparison='+8% vs mês anterior' />. Agent reads 500 tokens of doc → generates correct MetricCard usage. (3) **CI rules:** eslint-plugin-design-system (custom): rule 'no-raw-colors' (flags hardcoded hex/rgb). rule 'no-raw-spacing' (flags hardcoded px for padding/margin/gap). rule 'prefer-ds-component' (flags <div className='badge...'> when <StatusBadge> exists). rule 'token-reference' (flags CSS property values that don't use var(--*)). (4) **agent reviewer:** optional second-pass agent that reviews UI output for DS compliance before merge. Checks: all components from DS? All values from tokens? Consistent with existing pages?"
		meshImplication: "Governance implementation: (1) CLAUDE.md: 3 sections for UI: (a) available components (list with 1-line description each). (b) token usage rules ('use --color-* for colors, --spacing-* for gaps, --font-size-* for text'). (c) anti-patterns ('never: inline style with hex value. Never: custom badge when StatusBadge exists.'). Updated when: new component added, component API changes, new anti-pattern identified. (2) CI enforcement: start with: 'no-raw-colors' rule (highest impact, catches most inconsistency). Add rules incrementally. Each rule: warning first (agent learns), then error (enforced). (3) agent output review process: agent generates UI code → CI runs lint → if violations: agent receives feedback, fixes. If no violations: human reviews business logic (not visual consistency — DS + CI handled that). Human review effort: reduced from 'review every pixel' to 'review business logic only.' (4) new component process: agent encounters UI pattern not covered by DS → agent documents: 'need: [description], similar to: [existing component], proposed approach: [extend X or create Y].' Human reviews proposal. If approved: agent creates DS component with tokens + docs + tests. (5) DS metrics: % of UI code using DS components (target: >90%). % of visual properties using tokens (target: >95%). CI violations per PR (target: <2 new violations per PR, trending to 0). (6) minimal viable enforcement: for day 1, even without custom eslint plugin: CLAUDE.md instruction + post-session manual review is sufficient. CI enforcement: add when volume of agent sessions justifies automation investment. Anti-pattern: design system exists in Figma but not in code — beautiful designs that agents can't consume. DS must be code-first: component library in code + token CSS file. Figma is optional visualization, not source of truth."
		dependsOn: ["dt-token-architecture", "dt-component-composition"]
		crossDependsOn: [{
			lensId:    "lens-ai-agent-governance"
			conceptId: "aag-governance-as-code"
			context:   "AAG defines governance como código consultável por agentes: policies, boundaries, conventions. DT design system governance is the visual manifestation: tokens are visual policies (color-success-primary = this green), components are visual boundaries (use MetricCard, not custom div), CI rules are visual enforcement. AAG governs agent behavior broadly; DT governs agent visual output specifically. Together: agent produces code that is both architecturally sound (AAG) and visually consistent (DT)."
		}]
		rationale: "Design system as prompt 2024+. CI as enforcer 2024+. Na Mesh AI-native, design system is the constraint system that makes N agent sessions produce 1 visual style. Without DS governance: visual entropy increases with each agent session. With: visual consistency maintained automatically through tokens + components + CI. Solo founder doesn't review pixels — system governs."
	},
	{
		id:         "dt-minimal-viable-design-system"
		name:       "Minimal Viable Design System: Começar com o Suficiente, Expandir com Evidência"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "method"
		reviewCadence: "quarterly"
		definition: "Full design system (100+ components, comprehensive documentation, design tool integration, theme builder) takes months to build. For solo founder building MVP: months on design system = months without product. But no design system = visual chaos from day 1 that compounds. Conceito de 'minimal viable design system' (MVDS, 2023+): the smallest design system that prevents visual chaos while enabling rapid development. Includes: tokens (all visual values), core components (covers 80% of UI), and basic docs (agent can use components correctly). Expand: when evidence shows gap (pattern appears 3+ times without component, token is missing for common value). Conceito de 'invest-as-you-go' (2024+): DS investment proportional to product maturity. Pre-MVP: tokens + 10 components. MVP: tokens + 15-20 components + basic docs. Growth: tokens + 25-35 components + full docs + CI enforcement + theme support. Scale: tokens + 50+ components + design tool sync + multi-brand. Each stage: justified by current needs, not future speculation."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, MVDS for pre-MVP/MVP: **Phase 1 — Tokens (4 hours):** all visual values as CSS custom properties. Colors (semantic 5×3 + gray scale + brand = ~25). Spacing (9 steps). Font-size (6 steps per density). Font-weight (4). Border-radius (5). Shadow (4). Total: ~95 globals + ~50 aliases = ~145 tokens in 1 CSS file. **Phase 2 — 10 Core Components (30 hours):** Button, Input, Select, Badge/StatusBadge, MetricCard, DataTable (basic: header + rows + sort + pagination), FormField, Toast, Modal, Skeleton. These cover: dashboards (MetricCard + DataTable), forms (Input + FormField + Button + Select), feedback (Toast + Modal + Skeleton), status (StatusBadge). 80% of MVP UI covered. **Phase 3 — Basic Docs (8 hours):** each component: 1-page doc with props, usage guidelines, code example. CLAUDE.md section: available components + token usage rules. **Total Phase 1-3: ~42 hours.** Sufficient for: agent-generated UI with consistency, density modes (token override), and basic theming (light). **Phase 4 — Expand (ongoing):** add components as patterns emerge: Sparkline (when KPI cards need trend), CommandPalette (when 20+ actions), SidePanel (when drill-down pattern established), ActionBar (when batch operations built). Each: justified by usage ≥3 times."
		meshImplication: "MVDS implementation: (1) tokens FIRST — before any component. Even if building with raw Tailwind initially: create tokens.css that maps semantic names to Tailwind values. --color-success-primary: theme('colors.green.700'). When ready for custom components: tokens already exist. (2) 10 components by priority — ordered by: frequency of use × complexity of getting wrong. Button (used everywhere, states matter). Input (forms, critical for data entry). DataTable (FIDC + construtora primary interface). MetricCard (dashboard primary). StatusBadge (status everywhere). Toast (feedback everywhere). These 6 are highest priority. Next 4: Select, FormField, Modal, Skeleton. (3) build incrementally — day 1: tokens.css (4h). Day 2: Button + Input + Badge (8h). Day 3: MetricCard + Toast (6h). Day 4: DataTable (8h, most complex). Day 5: FormField + Select + Modal + Skeleton (8h). Day 6: docs (8h). Total: 6 days / 42 hours for complete MVDS. (4) agent workflow — agent reads CLAUDE.md → sees component list → uses components + tokens → CI validates. From day 6: every agent session produces consistent UI. Before day 6: agent uses Tailwind with token-mapped classes (acceptable for MVP, migrate to components when built). (5) what NOT to build yet — chart components (use Recharts/Chart.js with token-based styling). Dark mode (light first, dark later). Animation library (focus on function, not motion). Icon library (use Lucide CDN). Design tool sync (Figma variables sync — nice but not MVP). (6) expand trigger — 'I need a component that doesn't exist' appears 3 times → create it. 'This pattern is inconsistent across 3 pages' → component needed. 'Agent generated this differently than existing pattern' → component prevents recurrence. Anti-pattern: spend 3 months building comprehensive DS before writing any product code — DS without product to style is speculation. Or: spend 0 time on DS, build product with hardcoded values → visual chaos that takes 3 months to untangle later. MVDS: 42 hours prevents both extremes."
		dependsOn: ["dt-token-architecture", "dt-component-composition"]
		rationale: "MVDS 2023+. Invest-as-you-go 2024+. Na Mesh solo founder, 42 hours of DS investment prevents: visual inconsistency from day 1, agent-generated chaos, and costly retrofit later. 42 hours = 1 week. Product without DS: visual debt accrues at ~10 hours/month of inconsistency fixes. DS payback: <5 months."
	},
	{
		id:         "dt-spacing-system"
		name:       "Sistema de Spacing: Escala Consistente para Gaps, Padding e Margins"
		nature:     "operational"
		role:       "property"
		reviewCadence: "semi-annual"
		definition: "Spacing system define: how much space between and within elements. Base: 4px grid (most common in modern design systems — divisible into halves and quarters cleanly, aligns with common line-heights). Scale: geometric or linear progression based on 4px. Conceito de 'spacing roles' (2023+): different spacing values for different roles: (a) inline spacing — within component (padding, gap between icon and text). Small: 4-8px. (b) component spacing — between elements within a group (gap between form fields, gap between cards in row). Medium: 8-16px. (c) section spacing — between groups/sections (gap between KPI row and table, gap between page header and content). Large: 16-32px. (d) page spacing — margins, gutters, container padding. Largest: 24-48px. Conceito de 'spacing and density' (2024+): spacing role values shift per density mode. Compact: all values shrink by ~50%. Spacious: all values grow by ~50%. But role hierarchy is preserved: inline < component < section < page in all modes."
		meshManifestation: "Na Mesh, spacing scale: **Base grid: 4px.** Scale: step-1: 4px, step-2: 8px, step-3: 12px, step-4: 16px, step-5: 20px, step-6: 24px, step-8: 32px, step-10: 40px, step-12: 48px. **Role mapping (default mode):** --spacing-inline: step-2 (8px) — icon to text, badge padding horizontal. --spacing-component: step-4 (16px) — form fields gap, card internal padding. --spacing-section: step-6 (24px) — KPI row to table, header to content. --spacing-page: step-8 (32px) — page margins, container padding. **Density overrides:** compact: inline=4, component=8, section=12, page=16. Spacious: inline=12, component=24, section=32, page=48."
		meshImplication: "Spacing implementation: (1) 9-step scale as tokens: --spacing-1: 4px through --spacing-12: 48px. (2) role aliases: --spacing-inline: var(--spacing-2). --spacing-component: var(--spacing-4). --spacing-section: var(--spacing-6). --spacing-page: var(--spacing-8). (3) density overrides change role aliases, not component code: .density-compact { --spacing-component: var(--spacing-2); }. Component: .card { padding: var(--spacing-component); } — 16px default, 8px compact. (4) no arbitrary spacing: every margin, padding, and gap references token. If 18px is needed: it doesn't exist in scale → pick 16px or 20px. Scale enforces consistency. (5) Gestalt proximity: spacing between items within a group < spacing between groups. Card internal padding (16px) < gap between cards (24px). Table cell padding (8px) < gap between table and chart (24px). If within-group = between-group: grouping is invisible. (6) responsive spacing: mobile: --spacing-page = 16px (screen edge is close). Desktop: --spacing-page = 32px (ample room). Components: responsive via token. (7) testing: take any screen → measure spacing between elements. All on 4px grid? Role hierarchy preserved (inline < component < section)?"
		dependsOn: ["dt-token-architecture"]
		rationale: "Spacing roles 2023+. Spacing and density 2024+. Na Mesh, 9-step scale + 4 role aliases + density overrides = consistent spacing governed by tokens. No 'this looks like about 18px' — every space is from scale."
	},
