meshExamples: [
	{
		id:       "ex-token-based-density-switch"
		scenario: "Product needs to add compact density mode for FIDC. Currently all interfaces use default density with hardcoded spacing, font-sizes, and row heights. Estimated hardcoded values: 200+ occurrences across 30 component files."
		analysis: "Without tokens: adding compact mode requires finding and modifying 200+ hardcoded values, creating conditional logic in each component (if compact: 8px, else 16px), and testing each component individually. Estimated effort: 80-120 hours. With tokens: extract values to tokens (one-time), then override tokens in density mode class. Effort: extraction 30h + mode definition 4h + testing 8h = 42h. And: every future density change is token-only (minutes)."
		recommendation: "(1) Phase 1 — Token extraction (30h): systematically replace every hardcoded visual value with token reference. padding: 16px → padding: var(--spacing-component). font-size: 14px → font-size: var(--font-size-base). height: 36px → height: var(--table-row-height). 200+ replacements across 30 files. Use search-and-replace for common patterns, manual for complex cases. (2) Phase 2 — Mode definition (4h): create density mode CSS: .density-compact { --spacing-component: 8px; --font-size-base: 13px; --table-row-height: 24px; --kpi-card-padding: 12px; --line-height-tight: 1.2; ... }. All overrides in 1 CSS block. (3) Phase 3 — Apply and test (8h): add class='density-compact' to FIDC portal body. All components: automatically compact. Test: each screen in compact. Fix: any overflow or overlap (text that wraps in compact where it didn't in default). (4) Result: FIDC table shows ~30 rows instead of ~18 (67% improvement). KPI cards are tighter. Overall: more data per screen. (5) Ongoing benefit: future density adjustment = change token value. 'Table rows too tight?' → --table-row-height: 26px. Done. No component hunting. (6) ROI: token extraction (42h) vs per-feature density (80-120h) + ongoing maintenance (10h/quarter for manual sync). Payback: immediate. Plus: theme support (dark mode, white-label) becomes trivial — same token override pattern."
